  "Churn prediction helps businesses retain customers by identifying at-risk individuals before they leave.": "",
  "A hospital builds a regression model to predict patient readmission within 30 days using age, diagnosis severity, and length of stay. The model has r² = 0.42 on the training data and r² = 0.38 on the test data. What does the small difference in r² values suggest?": "",
  "The model is overfitting badly because the training r-squared is slightly higher than the testing": "",
  "The model is useless because r-squared is below 0.5 on the test data and cannot predict accurately": "",
  "The test set was too large, reducing the training data available and weakening the model's accuracy": "",
  "The model generalizes reasonably well — the small gap between training and testing r² indicates minimal overfitting": "",
  "A small drop from training to testing r² indicates the model captures real patterns rather than noise, even though moderate r² is common in healthcare.": "",
  "A weather service uses a regression model with 12 variables (temperature, humidity, wind speed, etc.) to predict rainfall. After 5-fold cross-validation, the average prediction error is 3.2 mm. If the model were only tested on its training data, the error would be 1.8 mm. Why is the cross-validation error higher?": "",
  "Cross-validation always produces larger r-squared numbers by design due to the averaging process": "",
  "The weather changed between folds, so each fold experienced fundamentally different climate patterns": "",
  "The model performs better on data it was trained on; cross-validation gives a more honest estimate of true prediction error on new data": "",
  "Cross-validation uses fewer variables, which automatically reduces the model's explanatory power": "",
  "Training error is optimistically low because the model has already seen those data; cross-validation provides a realistic estimate of out-of-sample performance.": "",
  "A sports analytics team predicts player performance using age, games played, and training hours. For a 25-year-old with 80 games and 500 training hours, the predicted score is 78 with a 95% prediction interval of (62, 94) and a 95% confidence interval for the mean of (74, 82). A scout asks 'Will this specific player score at least 70?' Which interval should be used?": "",
  "Neither interval is appropriate": "",
  "The point estimate of 78 is all that is needed": "",
  "The prediction interval (62, 94), because it accounts for individual variability — the question is about one specific player": "",
  "The confidence interval (74, 82), because it is more precise": "",
  "For predicting an individual outcome, the prediction interval is appropriate because it captures individual variation beyond just the mean.": "",
  "A retail company builds a sales forecast model in 2020. By 2023, online shopping has grown significantly and consumer behavior has shifted. The model's predictions are increasingly inaccurate. What should the company do?": "",
  "Abandon statistical modeling entirely": "",
  "Double the number of predictors without new data": "",
  "Update the model with recent data that reflects current shopping behavior and market conditions": "",
  "Continue using the 2020 model because it was accurate then": "",
  "When the underlying process changes (structural change), models must be refitted with recent data to remain accurate.": "",
  "An insurance company uses regression to predict annual claim costs from driver age, vehicle type, and driving record. They test three models: Model A (2 variables, r² = 0.45 on test), Model B (5 variables, r² = 0.52 on test), Model C (20 variables, r² = 0.48 on test). Which model is likely best?": "",
  "Model B — it has the highest test r², suggesting it captures real patterns without overfitting": "",
  "Model A — fewer variables is always best": "",
  "Model C — more variables always produce better predictions": "",
  "None of them because r² should be above 0.8": "",
  "Model C's lower test r² compared to B suggests overfitting from too many variables. Model B balances complexity and predictive power.": "",
  "A city uses regression to predict daily subway ridership from day of week, weather, and whether there is a special event. On a rainy Tuesday with a concert downtown, the model predicts 450,000 riders. The actual count was 485,000. The residual is:": "",
  "+35,000 (the actual ridership exceeded the prediction)": "",
  "−35,000 (the model overpredicted)": "",
  "0 (the model is perfect)": "",
  "450,000": "",
  "Residual = actual − predicted = 485,000 − 450,000 = +35,000. The positive residual means the model underpredicted.": "",
  "A bank uses a credit scoring model to predict loan default probability. The model was built on data from 2015-2019. During the 2020 pandemic, default rates changed dramatically and the model performed poorly. This illustrates:": "",
  "Credit scoring is not a valid use of regression because human behavior cannot be modeled statistically": "",
  "Regression models are always unreliable when applied to financial data with high natural variability": "",
  "The 2015-2019 data was collected incorrectly, so the model was flawed from the very beginning of development": "",
  "Models built on historical data may fail when unprecedented events change the underlying relationships, highlighting the need for model monitoring and updating": "",
  "Structural breaks — like a pandemic — violate the assumption that future data follows the same pattern as training data.": "",
  "A marketing team performs 10-fold cross-validation on a customer spending model. The model has r² = 0.65 on training and r² = 0.62 on average across the 10 test folds. The manager asks, 'Can we use this model for next quarter's budget planning?'": "",
  "No, the model is useless because r-squared is not above 0.8 on either training or testing data": "",
  "Only if r-squared equals 1 on training data, indicating the model captures all variation perfectly": "",
  "No, cross-validation shows the model cannot be used in practice since the r-squared varies by fold": "",
  "Yes — the consistent performance across folds (small gap) suggests the model is reliable for planning, though predictions will have some uncertainty": "",
  "Stable cross-validation results indicate reliable generalization; the model can inform planning while acknowledging the inherent uncertainty.": "",
  "A health clinic builds a model predicting blood pressure from BMI, age, and smoking status. An engineer suggests also adding shoe size and favorite color as predictors. What is likely to happen?": "",
  "Adding more variables always improves a model regardless of whether they are relevant to the outcome": "",
  "R-squared will increase substantially and predictions will improve once the new variables are included": "",
  "The model will reject the variables automatically through its built-in variable selection mechanism": "",
  "R² may increase slightly on training data, but the irrelevant variables will likely decrease adjusted R² and worsen predictions on new data (overfitting)": "",
  "Adding irrelevant predictors inflates R² through noise but hurts adjusted R² and test-set performance.": "",
  "A university admissions office uses a regression model to predict first-year GPA from SAT score, high school GPA, and extracurricular hours. They notice that after a new feature — parent income — is added, prediction improves significantly. However, using income raises ethical concerns about fairness. What should they consider?": "",
  "Ethics have no place in statistical modeling because accuracy is the only criterion that matters": "",
